HealthyLabs.AI Refinery Summary
1. Phase 1: The Extractor Pipeline (extractor.py)
The Extractor is an edge-side worker responsible for parsing raw medical documents,
executing optical character recognition (OCR), and uploading visual assets.
Core Logic:
• Primary Engine: Uses pypdfium2 to parse high-fidelity text, bounding boxes,
and layout graphs.
• Fallback Engine: If pypdfium2 fails or hits unreadable text (0 text density), it
triggers Tesseract OCR.
• Asset Processing: Extracts images, tables, and diagrams, immediately pushing
the visual assets to MinIO (S3) and retaining the MinIO URI.
• Quality Guardrail: Calculates a holistic quality score based on text density and
OCR confidence. If the score falls below the EXTRACTOR_QUALITY_THRESHOLD
(currently 0.30), the document is flagged to prevent garbage data from polluting
the graph.
2. Phase 2: The Refinery API Gateway (main.py)
The FastAPI endpoint (/refinery/v1/ingest) is the central orchestrator. It receives
the JSON payload from the Extractor and enforces strict security and idempotency rules
before persisting data.
The Processing Gates:
1. Idempotency Gatekeeper: Queries PostgreSQL to check if the document_id or
content_hash already exists. If yes, it aborts silently (200 OK,
decision="skipped_duplicate").
2. Safety & PHI Engine: Scans the raw text for Protected Health Information (PHI).
If the PHI density exceeds the PHI_CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD (currently 0.20),
the document status is forcibly changed to QUARANTINED.
3. Relational Persistence: Writes the document metadata, audit logs, and table
structures into PostgreSQL.
4. Async Handoff: If the document survives all gates (Status = ACTIVE), the API
returns a 200 OK to the Extractor and passes the payload to a background
worker for chunking and embedding.
3. Phase 3: Graph & Vector Generation (Background Task)
This phase transforms the raw text into a hierarchical, semantically searchable format
suitable for Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG).
• Hierarchical Chunking: * L2 (ClinicalContext): Broad, document-level chunks
that capture the surrounding narrative and section hierarchy.
o L1 (AtomicChunk): Small, precise snippets of text derived directly from
their parent L2 chunk.
• Embedding Model: Uses BioLORD-2023. Every L1 Atomic Chunk is converted
into a 768-dimensional dense vector float array.
• Knowledge Graph (KG) Extraction: A secondary service (kg_service.py)
scans the document for explicit medical entities (e.g., prescriptions, dosages)
and creates explicit node relationships.
4. Data Formats & Schemas
A. The Wire Format (Pydantic Validation)
This is the JSON payload the Extractor sends to the API. All arrays and sub-objects use
default factories (Optional, [], or None) to prevent 422 Unprocessable Entity
errors if a document is missing specific elements.
JSON
{
 "document_id": "sha256_hash_string",
 "content": "Raw extracted text...",
 "source": "url_or_filepath",
 "metadata": {
 "title": "Optional[str]",
 "published_at": "Optional[datetime]",
 "tags": ["cardiology", "guidelines"]
 },
 "quality": {
 "overall_score": 0.85,
 "ocr_mean_confidence": 0.92,
 "issues": []
 },
 "assets": [
 {
 "asset_id": "uuid",
 "kind": "extracted_image",
 "path": "s3://healthylabs-images/...",
 "page": 12
 }
 ],
 "tables": [],
 "medical_patterns": []
}
B. PostgreSQL (Metadata & Provenance Layer)
PostgreSQL acts as the source of truth for document state, auditing, and structured
table data.
• MedicalMetadata Table: Stores the document master record.
o document_id (PK, String)
o content_hash (String, Unique)
o status (Enum: ACTIVE, QUARANTINED, DEPRECATED)
o authority_score (Float)
• MedicalMetadataAudit Table: An append-only ledger tracking every state
change (e.g., why a document was quarantined for PHI or flagged for
contradictions).
• MedicalTable Table: Stores extracted tables as flat CSV strings for easy
downstream parsing.
• MedicalAsset Table: Maps asset UUIDs to their MinIO storage_path.
C. MinIO (Object Storage)
A local S3-compatible datastore.
• Bucket: healthylabs-images
• Contents: Raw .png or .jpg files extracted from the PDFs (diagrams, scans,
DICOM renders). These are linked via the Neo4j graph and PostgreSQL via their
S3 paths.
D. Neo4j (Vector & Knowledge Graph Layer)
This is the database the downstream model will query to perform RAG.
1. The Vector Index An index named atomic_chunk_embedding sits on the
embedding property of AtomicChunk nodes. It is configured for 768 dimensions using
cosine similarity.
2. The Graph Topology The model developer will traverse this structure to retrieve
context:
• (d:Document) Node:
o Properties: document_id, doc_uid, updated_at
• (c:ClinicalContext) Node [L2 Chunk]:
o Properties: id, content (large text block), level (int: 2), metadata
(Stringified JSON containing section headers and layout rules).
o Relationship: (c)-[:CHILD_OF]->(d)
• (a:AtomicChunk) Node [L1 Chunk]:
o Properties: id, content (precise text snippet), embedding (List[Float],
768-dim), tier, authority_score.
o Relationship: (a)-[:PART_OF]->(c)
Retrieval Strategy for the Model: When the model receives a user query, it should:
1. Embed the user query using BioLORD-2023.
2. Perform a vector similarity search against the AtomicChunk nodes.
3. Once the top K AtomicChunk nodes are found, traverse the graph up (MATCH
(a)-[:PART_OF]->(c:ClinicalContext)) to retrieve the surrounding L2
context and stringified metadata, feeding that enriched context into the LLM
prompt.